<font color="#FF0000">MISCONCEPTIONS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 14  8:31:19 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
   There are so many misconceptions in this thread, I would like to add a few comments.  I am especially disturbed at the comparisons between Clinton“s plans to bomb Iraq and the Vietnam War.<br>
   First, Saddam Hussein“s power was given to him by us.  The United States and our allies armed him to the teeth and gave him secret intelligence reports while he was fighting against Iran.  His poison gas factory was built by West German engineers at the behest of the United States.  It was supposed to be a herbicide factory.  Before he invaded Kuwait, he asked the American ambassador whether the United States would object to his occupying Kuwait, and, according to her testimony before Congress, she told him that Kuwait was outside of the sphere of interest of the United States.<br>
   The fanatical Moslems frequently mentioned are Shiites, the dominant form of Islam in Iran.  The population of Iraq is mainly Sunnite, and they are not prone to radicalism.  During the Gulf War, we encouraged the Shiite minority in the South and the Kurds in the North to rebel against Sadam Hussein, and they did.  When the United States left, the Shiites and the Kurds were systematically slaughtered by Saddam Hussein, and President Bush said that this was an internal affair of Iraq.<br>
   There is no more Soviet Union, and the Russians are trying their best to introduce democracy.  To get rid of the communists, large numbers of Russians and citizens of the other countries of the former Soviet Union that had been oppressed by the communists had to stand up to tanks.  I do not think that they should be placed in the role of the villains here.  Russia just fought a bloody war in their autonomous provinces in the South, which are predominantly Moslem, and they naturally have worries about being faced with more religious wars if the Moslems in the Middle East are provoked and feel themselves threatened by overbearing military power.<br>
   The danger with Clinton“s new adventure is that he may cause our many allies in the Middle East to lose power to radical groups.  At the present time, there is little danger of war there because most of the countries have moderate leaders.  However, there is a bloody war in Algeria involving Moslem fundamentalists against the government.  There are terrorist groups trying to topple the Egyptian government.  There are terrorist acts in Saudi Arabia.  Right now, pro-American governments are still in charge.  What happens when pictures start coming out of Iraq showing the bodies of women and kids blown up by American bombs?  This also comes at a time when the peace process between the Israelis and Palestinians is falling apart.  There might be uprisings against the moderate governments of the Moslem countries, and a new combination of powers might suddenly appear.  The United States might be faced with the choice of fighting a major war or letting Israel get wiped out.  This is why America“s biggest allies in the region, Jordan and Saudi Arabia, do not want to have anything to do with the bombing of Iraq.  The kings do not want to get overthrown.<br>
   This is the danger of having a president without military experience.  He has no idea of the things that can go wrong, and he probably does not care because he and his friends know that they will not have to risk their own lives.<br>
   At the start of the Vietnam War, America was faced with an expanding Communist empire that had been taking over country after country through terrorist methods.  Americans perceived their own freedom threatened by major nuclear powers: the Soviet Union and China.  Eisenhower and Kennedy saw Vietnam as a possible place to hold the line, preventing communist expansion into the other former colonies that were becoming independent.  It was a war to keep America from becoming isolated by an imperialist giant, and it was considered to be a war vital enough for American survival by five consecutive presidents to commit large amounts of money and to risk the lives of several million American fighting men.  It was also a war against an enemy that would stop at nothing to force its will on the populations of South Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia at the point of a gun.  We still do not even know how many Vietnamese, Laotians, and Cambodians were killed after the communist victory, but we do know that the number of murdered civilians ran into the millions in Cambodia alone.<br>
   Iraq is not part of any ominous empire.  It is a tiny country ruled by one crazy man who we ourselves armed to the teeth and constructed poison gas factories for.  The only reason it is of such great interest is its possession of a large proportion of the world“s oil supply. If we bomb it, we will be killing many civilians but almost certainly not Saddam Hussein.<br>
   As for chemical and biological weapons, we have considerable evidence that such weapons were used in Laos, probably by the Vietnamese.  Remember those reports?  If so, the communists in Vietnam must also possess chemical and biological weapons.  Does President Clinton want to bomb Hanoi again?  How many other countries are working on chemical or biological weapons?  Should we bomb them all?  These weapons can be manufactured in any basement.  Remember the fanatical sect that killed a number of people with chemical weapons in the Tokyo subway?<br>
   The final misconception is that the anti-Vietnam protestors were on the side of the veterans.  I found this a particularly disgusting assertion in view of the fact that I have been refused all employment opportunity in the United States for almost 30 years because I fought in the Vietnam War.  Because I work as a scientist, I am forced to seek employment abroad because of discrimination by former protestors in the United States.  At the present time, they dominate the academic professions because by staying on as students at the time, they were able avoid serving in the armed forces during the war.  This was confirmed by three different New York State employment specialists who each told me that I will never be hired by a university or research institute in the United States because at least one member of every selection committee dodged the draft during the Vietnam War and would &quot;feel uncomfortable working with a veteran.&quot;<br>
   
